[[<-|Interactive Comedy]] [[Index]]Comedy Comedy has been an object of discussion for centuries, among comedians, theorists, and philosophers alike. Yet every attempt to categorically define what makes something funny has failed to include every instance of humor. Three primary comic theories throughout history—superiority theory, incongruity theory, and relief theory—each prescribe their titular quality as quintessential to comedy (Clayton 9-12). To account for these individual failings, comedy could be considered “irreducibly compound” (Clayton 47). We can try to formalize it, but ultimately comedy is subjective: as the saying goes, funny is funny. That does not make critique or analysis purposeless, but “that you have to focus on how it tries to achieve its funny and what it is trying to communicate, instead of debating if something is funny at all” (Fox 72). In breaking down its layers, Clayton proposes five ways of answering “Why do we laugh?”: causal, which identifies the stimulus of laughter; motivational, which identifies the purpose or intent of laughter; functional, which identifies the social or biological advantages of laughter; perceptual, which identifies the personal preferences to lead someone to find something funny; and aesthetic, which identifies the traits of a comic object that render it funny to an audience (13-14). When considering digital artifacts, the most relevant facets to this question are causal and aesthetic. How interactive media causes players to laugh, and its qualities that can be comedic, are important considerations for this context. Important concepts include: [[The Joke]] [[Play Theory]] [[Trust]] [[Theory of Comic Objects]] Some subgenres of comedy are: [[Literary Comedy]] [[Burlesque]] [[Sketch]] [[Slapstick]] [[Standup]] [[<-|Interactive Comedy]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Interactive Comedy We’re dealing with a classic squares-and-rectangles dichotomy: my research revolves around games that are funny, but it does not concern all funny games. Most notably, //Funny Games//, the 1997 film, is no concern of mine. I use the term interactive comedy to mean any instance of comedy where the user’s input is unquestionably part of the humor. Clicking through witty dialogue or watching a goofy cutscene between gameplay segments do not meaningfully make use of the interactive medium. The focus in this context is on digital media and “played objects that are only mobilized by the action of the playing subject” (Atkins and Krzywinska 3). If removing the interactive layer does not change the audience experience, then it is not relevant to this research. Mimicking the oft-cited concept of ludonarrative dissonance, another proposed term for this topic is “ludo-comedic consonance” (Giappone et al. 2). While this phrase is useful in its own right, ludology is a field of study particularly interested in game mechanics, and one that defines itself as separate from narratology. This term feels limiting, as my interest is in both ludology and narratology, which present different ways for interactive media to allow for the user to engage with a work. Instead, I choose to say interactive comedy. [[Playable Media]] [[Comedy]] [[Convergences]] [[<-|Start]] [[Index]] [[Image]] Playable Media Playable media, for our purposes, is any digital interactive media where the user has a role in the construction of the text. This makes not just every user’s experience with the text different, but the texts they experience different as well. I chose the term playable to avoid redundancy with interactive comedy, and because I feel play implies a digital interface. Important concepts include: [[Puzzle]] [[Participatory]] [[Unnatural Narrative]] [[Antimimeticism]] [[Medium Specificity]] [[Metalepsis]] Specific forms of playable media include: [[Hypertext]] [[Videogame]] [[Interactive Fiction]] [[<-|Interactive Comedy]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Participatory I do not need to cite a definition of participatory; it is not a word unique to ludology. By interacting with media, players engage with it in a fundamentally different way than the passive process of reading or viewing. The sense of agency present in playable media, while not unique to the digital space, is a defining characteristic of it. There are any number of possible degrees of agency, but its presence at all represents a paradigm shift when compared to static texts. Participatory intersects with: [[The Joke]] at [[Interactive Gags]] [[Play Theory]] at [[Play Contract]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Unnatural Narrative A narrative is unnatural if it is impossible in our world. Most instances within unnatural narratology belong to three larger categories: “unnatural storyworlds, which are settings where impossible things happen; unnatural minds, typically pertaining to characters and narrators with impossible human qualities, such as omniscience or various kinds of psychopathological conditions `[]`; and unnatural acts of narration, such as second-person narration” (Bell and Ensslin 83-84). An important thing to note about unnatural narrative is that it is not necessarily unconventional or unfamiliar. By definition, all fantasy stories include fantastical, magical elements, which we readily acknowledge as untrue, and yet they never serve to defamiliarize or estrange the audience. We accept these as the nature of the storyworld, and as long as the internal logic remains consistent, we do not question their capacity to exist. Unnatural narrative and [[antimimeticism|Antimimeticism]] often go hand in hand, but they are not the same. Unnatural Narrative intersects with: [[Trust]] at [[Betraying Trust]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Medium Specificity Medium-specificity (some authors choose to hyphenate it, others do not) is, simply put, the consideration of features unique to a particular form. For videogames, the focus of Giappone et al.’s book, there are three primary aspects: “their computational nature and the simulated worlds they take place in; the interaction between the player and the game; and the conventions of game design” (14). Extended to hypertext or interactive fiction, medium-specific traits might be hyperlinks, discrete text passages, or a command line for input. Medium Specificity intersects with: [[Theory of Comic Objects]] at [[Convention as Setup]] [[Literary Comedy]] at [[Limitation as Setup]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Metalepsis Metalepsis is “the movement of entities between ontologically distinct spheres” (Bell and Ensslin 49), or crossing between logically disconnected worlds. The primary spheres in the ontology of fiction are the Actual World, in which we live, and the Textual Actual World, as depicted by the text (Bell 186). There is also the “‘text space’ of the storyworld” between these layers, containing the discourse and presentation of the narrative (Bell and Ensslin 59). For the example of hypertext, we recognize the real world, the story described, and the interface of text passages which players navigate by cursor as three distinct spaces, yet there remains the possibility for movement between them, most notably the player’s intrusion into the other two layers. Interactional metalepsis is a convention of many interactive works. It happens when the player inhabits a character in the fictional world, or a facet of the text such as a cursor, in doing so crossing “the actual-world-to-storyworld boundary” (49). This is especially apparent in first-person games when you, in the actual world, embody the avatar character you directly control, seeing the game world from their perspective. When the player has such a counterpart onscreen, this is necessarily a logical impossibility: your presence in the actual world cannot extend to the digital space, and yet it must to play the game (57). This ontological transgression, while nearly unseen in other media, is highly conventionalized in digital interactive works. Metalepsis intersects with: [[Burlesque]] at [[Casting Characters]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Hypertext Hypertext is a form of digital media in which the reader/player moves between passages of text by clicking hyperlinked words. Hypertext intersects with: [[Sketch]] at [[Sketched World]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Videogame Videogame is entirely too broad of a term, and one that benefits from further distinction. For interactive comedy, however, their shared traits are more interesting than how they diverge. One definition offered by Atkins and Krzywinska is “played objects that are only mobilized by the action of the playing subject” (3). For the purposes of this model, they are distinct from hypertext and IF for their stronger ludic focus and visual component. Videogame intersects with: [[Slapstick]] at [[Initiated Slapstick]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Interactive Fiction Interactive fiction (IF) embraces the idea of a “literary machine,” a term Montfort uses to combine “that of an assembled text as literary and that of the computer as a machine that manipulates symbols” (66). IF is a primarily text-based medium that asks typed inputs of the user, and these keyboard commands are how they move through the Textual World. They follow from the tradition of riddles, presenting the player with something to solve, and providing a satisfying solution that may reveal, among other things, “the disturbing nature of the world, leaving one with other worries and plenty to think about” (62). IF typically enables exploration, discovery, and experimentation. Interactive Fiction intersects with: [[Standup]] at [[Yes-Anding]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Puzzle Puzzles are things that you solve. Unfortunately, I did not come across any academic definitions of puzzle, though they are undoubtedly out there. For this context, a puzzle must have a “correct” answer, or at least have a certain way the player is meant to “solve” it. It can be any obstacle that impedes progress, narratively, spatially, or a secret third option I’m not telling you. Puzzle intersects with: [[The Joke]] at [[Puzzle Punchlines]] [[Index]] [[Image]]The Joke There are two kinds of jokes: jokes, and joke-jokes. In the general sense, “a ‘joke’ is a complete comedic idea” (Fox 14). Like an atom, it is the smallest discrete unit of humor, from which all comic media is built. As long as it’s funny, a joke “can be anything to a comedian,” from a fact to a story to a secret third option I’m not sharing with you (Fox 13-14). Joke-jokes are a subset of joke that Fox defines as “freestanding, authorless, utilitarian tools to produce laughter” (13-14). They have more particular structures than a comedian’s jokes, like a knock-knock or a setup-punchline couplet, but they are discrete comedic ideas all the same. The Joke intersects with: [[Puzzle]] at [[Puzzle Punchlines]] [[Participatory]] at [[Interactive Gags]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Play Theory Play theory, a more recent proposition in the world of comic theory, posits comedy as a state of being in the audience, not a concrete instance in the text. Through this lens, jokes are "the means by which comedians play" (Fox 16). As with the other comic theories, this one has faced opposition; some criticize its “focus on the connection between laughter—not humor—and play” (Hurley et al. 39). However, play theory suggests “that humor evolved out of play” as the reason for their “shared expression” of laughter (Hurley et. al 39-40). I recognize that play and humor are separate ideas, but their connection is substantive enough to me to warrant further discussion of play in the context of comedy studies. Play Theory intersects with: [[Participatory]] at [[Play Contract]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Trust Following from [[Play Theory]], trust is an important part of preparing an audience for comedy. Especially in live contexts like standup, comedians “artificially create that state of play by generating the same feelings of trust and safety that free you up to laugh most easily” (Fox 16). This trust also allows the audience to “tap into the`[ir]` juvenile self” by relieving pressure to perform a certain way (Fox 66). Trust translates interestingly into the interactive space. If we consider the digital artifact the surrogate comedian, trust comes from allowing the player freedom to explore all the interactions they can think of, and most obviously limitations on agency would similarly risk losing player’s trust in the media to reward their input and curiosity, though there are certainly other ways for media to break the player’s trust. Trust intersects with: [[Unnatural Narrative]] at [[Betraying Trust]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Theory of Comic Objects Of the various attempts at defining, the most relevant to interactive comedy is Grodal’s generalized theory of comic entertainment, as described in Murphy’s essay. Its five steps for crafting humor (discussed in the context of a videogame) are as follows: 1) Priming the audience for a “comic event,” which can entail a setup of any kind (Murphy 63); 2) A “psychophysiologically arousing situation” to grab the player’s attention (63); 3) A “reality status appraisal,” in which the player assesses whether the outcome of the situation or their action has consequences for the game world and narrative, their in-game performance, or if the event is simply inappropriate or absurd (64); 4) The player’s reaction shifts to positive and humorous if the situation is deemed “‘not-real’, not-serious’, or ‘inconsequential’” (64); 5) The player’s experience of mirth, in setting a comedic tone, “may act as a springboard, in turn priming for or colouring the perception of further comic events” (66). As an aside, note how a comedic tone doubling as priming for future jokes resembles the concept of [[Play Theory]]. Theory of Comic Objects intersects with: [[Antimimeticism]] at [[Ambiguous Action]] [[Medium Specificity]] at [[Convention as Setup]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Literary Comedy Literary comedy, when compared to other forms, is most notable for its limitations. The “first four seconds” of a stage performance contain “a burst of sense-making activity as the spectator attempts to gain purchase on the terrain of the stage world” (Weitz 28). In terms of capacity for first impressions, literature lacks many techniques to let audiences set expectations for the work as a whole, privy to nothing but words. Genre framing is how authors “supply a mood, tone or atmosphere to the world of an unfolding text” (Weitz 23). Without the support of any other information, literary must be deliberate and persistent in setting the precedent for humor. Literary Comedy intersects with: [[Medium Specificity]] at [[Limitation as Setup]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Burlesque Burlesque as a performance is a variety style for which one of the main draws was striptease. For a comic, it is an oral tradition where performers memorized and circulated “comedy scenes, monologues, jokes, and bits of business” (Davis 2). The central piece of burlesque were these shared bits (ix). Individual comedians used them as starting points for incorporating their well-rehearsed character into the situation (54). As the sketches were always from memory, the same bit could vary wildly depending on the comics’ characters and improvised choices, but they would still be identifiable as the same concept. Bits were performed between variety acts, and were often started or ended with unrelated “entrance gags” and “tags or cappers” respectively, a separate shared pool of knowledge for making a bit a full comedic scene (90-91). Burlesque intersects with: [[Metalepsis]] at [[Casting Characters]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Sketch Sketch comedy starts “from a ‘what-if’ conceit and plays out a line of action” (Clayton 71). A single sketch takes one concept as far as it can, and these disconnected scenes are strung together to form a variety show of sorts. Sketch intersects with: [[Hypertext]] at [[Sketched World]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Slapstick Slapstick is a corporeal form of comedy. It’s not always physical, and it’s not always visual, but the idea at its core is the physicality of our bodies and the world around us. Slapstick gags, like the classic slipping-on-a-banana-peel, may “generate`[]` a link between the body and its environment in a way that, on the one hand, harms the body and, on the other, provokes laughter, as it suggests a reversal of the subject-object relation” (Lyons and Malakaj 75). Slapstick intersects with: [[Videogame]] at [[Initiated Slapstick]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Standup Standup is generally a monologue in front of an audience. If there were to be a holistic definition, it would have three pillars: personality, direct communication, and present tense (Double 19). Standup is a live act with an intense interaction between performer(s) and audience. The improvised aspects of the show are determined by how the audience reacts to the comic, and their presence in the same space as the audience matters. And when it comes to the comedian, “a stand-up’s personality is absolutely crucial to `[their]` act” (Double 59). Be it their authentic self or a caricature (or more likely a mix of the two), the performed character undoubtedly affects the success of a stand-up’s act (73). Standup intersects with: [[Interactive Fiction]] at [[Yes-Anding]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Puzzle Punchlines Hessler’s Essay proposes puzzle punchlines as a term for when “semantic tension between mechanics and presentation or ludic genre conventions or both enables humorous ambiguity” in puzzle solving (Hessler 77). With the titular example of the rubber chicken (technically RUBBER CHICKEN WITH A PULLEY IN THE MIDDLE), players must first use the pulley within to “fly” on a cable over a chasm, and then used in a stew recipe to substitute for “1 Live Chicken” (81-82). The humor from puzzle punchlines comes from applying items whose “affordance[s] to the player [are] initially ambiguous” (81). Much like interactive gags, the player is the one to perform the comic action (87). Hessler differentiates two primary types of puzzle punchlines. The crossroads model sets up an incongruity for which the resolution comes when the player solves the puzzle (81). The punchline comes from an unexpected application of a previously enigmatic object, like the aforementioned rubber chicken. The garden-path model similarly tasks the player to use something atypically, but this variant is named “after the expression to lead someone up the garden-path” because designers have set up false expectations or a red herring of sorts for the player (78). Both examples of puzzle punchline rely on an unexpected solution, but where the crossroads uses an ambiguous setup, the garden-path actively misleads users. Puzzle Punchlines is at the intersection of: [[The Joke]] and [[Puzzle]] [[<-|Convergences]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Interactive Gags Murphy’s essay defines an interactive gag as any in which the player must “unfold the joke rather than merely witnessing it” (54). As co-authors of the text, players have “mutually enacted” a joke alongside its writers when their interaction is a key part of its construction (54). In bringing the player into the unfolding humor, the timing is set by the audience, not the performer, an entirely different paradigm from most comedy. Interactive gags and interactive comedy may seem like synonyms at a glance, but by my definition they share the same relationship as jokes and comedy. Jokes are a foremost aspect of comedy, but comedy encompasses more than just a collection of jokes. It is worth exploring more facets of interactive comedy than just the interactive gag, especially interactive comic entertainment, to understand the underlying techniques and structures of the form. Interactive Gags is at the intersection of: [[The Joke]] and [[Participatory]] [[<-|Convergences]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Play Contract Consider the ludological idea of the magic circle: in stepping into the imaginary circle, players opt in to the laws of that space and accept them as truth in the context of play. In the words of Giappone et al., “games may require a steadfast commitment to arbitrary rules that may seem ridiculous and irrational” (3). Play contract is my term for this idea as it applies to interactive comedy: the audience must continuously choose to keep playing along with not only the game, but also the bit. It bears noting that “play” has different definitions between comic theory and ludology. Play theory in comedy is specifically about the audience relieving pressure and opening up to where the performer wants to go. In games, players often have a predetermined goal that makes this state of play harder to reach, such as reaching the final boss or speedrunning within a certain time. I argue, therefore, that the ideal comic play contract happens in interactive experiences without concrete goals. Juul’s essay “Without a Goal: On Open and Expressive Games” argues that when there is no goal (or no pressure to reach it) in the play experience, such as party games or replaying, we can “consider games as vehicles of expression” (Atkins and Krzywinska 198). One such form of expression is interactive comedy. This does not prevent more linear or more “serious” games from being funny, only that they do not as easily set players up for humor. Just as players must opt in to accept a game world’s rules as true, they must also choose to play the game as it was intended; they can just as easily choose to ignore an intended path or a grim atmosphere. The play contract is a comedic lens the player can choose to see through whether or not the game encourages it, and humor will be easier to find if they are seeking it out. Play Contract is at the intersection of: [[Play Theory]] and [[Participatory]] [[<-|Convergences]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Betraying Trust Trust in playable media depends on the interface working as expected and not arbitrarily restricting player agency. Consistency is key. But as digital media uniquely affords logical impossibilities and unnatural constructions, it has more means than other forms to break that consistency and betray the player’s trust. This idea has already been explored by creators and analysts alike, but the focus has always been on how these techniques can serve the story’s themes or intent. If the intent is comedy, how can unnatural narrative support a text’s humor? To start with, it is disingenuous to say an audience trusts a digital work in the same way they would trust a live performer. Beyond noting that one of those is human in its own right, digital media is essentially a tool for a story experience. When a player decides to play a game, they do not place trust in it, but rather expectations. To narrow the question, how can a digital work subvert player expectations in service of comedy? Expectations is deliberately a vague term here; players expect certain story progressions, modes of interaction, degrees of agency, elements of presentation, cause and effect, etc. None of these are necessarily universal, of course, but anywhere assumptions are made about the media in question, it has room to subvert them. I believe these subversions can be humorous by more than just the virtue of being unexpected. However, exploring this any further is beyond the scope of this research. Betraying Trust is at the intersection of: [[Trust]] and [[Unnatural Narrative]] [[<-|Convergences]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Ambiguous Action An important part of Grodal’s theory of comic entertainment is the reality status appraisal, where the audience assesses whether or not the result of their action was consequential, relevant, or appropriate within the story world. Antimimetic techniques could delay a successful reality status appraisal by obscuring the diegetic reality of the text. This would allow designers to mess with the pacing of the humor, as the punchline comes when the outcome is deemed insignificant, and the tension of not knowing is resolved. Another use of antimimeticism for comedy would be deliberately misinterpreting a player’s input, in a monkey’s paw-esque fashion. The literary machine is not functioning as expected, and under certain conditions this has the potential for humor. When the player is alienated from the world of the text, as antimimetic narrative seeks to do, they must move through the text using an incomplete understanding, creating potential for incongruity and comedy. As an example, imagine a scenario where action prompts are presented to the player in a saloon. One of the prompts reads “exit” and when clicked a background character gets up and exits the saloon. If clicked repeatedly, a different character leaves each time, but never the one the player typically controls. It is ambiguous what the player’s connection to the game world is as an interloper, and also unclear how to actually exit the saloon. This example is antimimetic by going against the conventions and expectations of the medium. And your avatar is not in any danger, so the outcome is certainly not consequential. It runs the risk of being more annoying than funny, and that is certainly a danger for comedic antimimeticism: when playfully alienating the player, it is feasible for them to feel like the target of the joke, not someone laughing. This area warrants more attention, beyond the scope of this research project. Ambiguous Action is at the intersection of: [[Theory of Comic Objects]] and [[Antimimeticism]] [[<-|Convergences]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Convention as Setup In a way, the interactive gag is the quintessential example of convention as setup. It takes interaction—the defining characteristic of playable media—and makes it part of the joke. More broadly, convention as setup uses the conventions of its specific medium in the construction of humor. It is closely related to ambiguous action, as both examples use the conventions of a medium as tools for comedy, but where the other acts in defiance of those norms, convention as setup embraces them. In his essay “Game Design as Narrative Architecture”, Jenkins proposes four main ways narrative occurs in game environments: evoked, enacts, embedded, or emergent. These four styles of environmental storytelling are very typical of audiovisual works, and as convention for interactive narrative they can similarly be applied to comedy. Evoked comedy calls to mind a past humorous context, and in doing so primes them for comic events; enacted comedy is directly experienced by the player; embedded comedy plays out the joke around the player as they explore their surroundings; and emergent comedy comes about organically from the player experimenting with the systems around them, other players, or both. Convention as Setup is at the intersection of: [[Theory of Comic Objects]] and [[Medium Specificity]] [[<-|Convergences]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Limitation as Setup One of the most notable features of literary comedy is its limitation. Communicating humor through text alone is a difficult task that requires deliberate and precise writing. For limitation as setup, the humor follows directly from what is impossible in a specific medium. I differentiate it from convention as setup by its focus on what the text cannot do, rather than what it can and often will do. This intersection has close ties to both convention as setup and antimimeticism, as all three draw on the context of their medium to make something funny. However, I think these being distinct categories is useful from a design standpoint. They can remind designers to consider their chosen medium from various angles: what is expected, what is impossible, and what can we do with those answers? As a general rule, casting a wider net when drafting allows for the creation of a more refined product, and these are some ways to consider new ideas when making interactive comedy. Limitation as Setup is at the intersection of: [[Literary Comedy]] and [[Medium Specificity]] [[<-|Convergences]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Casting Characters What if a storyworld had multiple distinct ontological realms? How would characters move through a narrative of that sort? One potential option is a literal translation of burlesque, and characters who at different times play the same parts, adding their own flair to it given their personality. There is great potential for emergent storytelling in seeing how different characters perform the same part, and how they interact with each other in these imposed roles. Beyond the strict interpretation of burlesque into fictional actors playing the same characters, there are more ways to apply the idea of role shuffling in an interactive way. One way seen a lot is strategy games, where certain players or characters have a specific task for the team (DPS, tank, healer, ranged, etc.). Strategy is notably a very goal-oriented game context, which is not ideal for comedy (see Play Contract), but that does not mean the same idea cannot be applied to multiplayer or party games. For example, take SpyParty (2018), a silly two-player game in which one person blends in with a crowd of non-player characters, and the other is tasked with finding them out and shooting them without hitting any NPCs. Its premise implements distinct roles that can be filled by any player, and part of the fun of this game is switching who plays which part. Casting Characters is at the intersection of: [[Burlesque]] and [[Metalepsis]] [[<-|Convergences]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Sketched World Hypertext allows for a player to exhaustively check every last option available on pre-scripted paths, which synergizes well with sketch comedy's structure of exploring one bit to its fullest. In a sketched world, players are empowered to engage with an initial premise however they see fit, thereby giving them control of how far the joke is taken in any given direction. Save for a completionist mindset, there is no reason for the audience to explore beyond the parts of the text they find funny. Thus, player agency in sketched worlds keeps the playing experience continuously entertaining. The Stanley Parable (2013) is a great example of this design in action. Though not a hypertext, the game allows players to move through the world in a number of directions, and the narrator responds accordingly. Its humor takes one core what-if (...the narrator was wrong?) and explores it to its comedic end in a number of directions. Sketched World is at the intersection of: [[Sketch]] and [[Hypertext]] [[<-|Convergences]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Initiated Slapstick Garin comments on the parallels between slapstick silent films and the Super Smash Bros. series: namely, their shared practice of crafting larger scenes from “interchangeable gestures” enacted between characters (108). Through embodying a character in a game that ludically centers physicality—such as a fighter in a platform fighting game—players can use the language of physical humor to play with their surroundings, be that a dynamic environment or other players. Fighting game examples certainly center violence, but a “subgenre of indie games—so-called fumblecore—has specialized in ridiculing player effort” (Giappone et al. 17). When movement itself is the primary obstacle to progression, games can allow players to laugh at their own pitiful attempts forward, creating physical humor in the same way slapstick does. Initiated Slapstick is at the intersection of: [[Slapstick]] and [[Videogame]] [[<-|Convergences]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Yes-Anding Standup comedy is the most improvisational comic form—aside from improv, but seeing as its defining quality is a lack of structure, I did not see it relevant to study in regards to interactive comedy. Standup, however, has a more apparent relevance to this domain: the comedian’s set is linear and pre-determined, but they adapt depending on audience feedback and interaction. When applied to something like IF, these principles of standup make space for interactive comedy that allows for diversions and exploration. Yes-anding is the text rewarding a player’s curiosity with a punchline, setups for additional jokes, or both. As the comic object, the text is the surrogate performer, and ultimately the one in charge of where the narrative is capable of going, but as the audience the player can steer it to include certain routes or take certain paths that are not necessarily the default. I differentiate yes-anding from sketched world by the means of interaction. In this context, players must think of unique interactions to stray from the expected path, whereas in a sketched world context the options are more readily presented; the difference is whether an idea is chosen from curiosity or preference. This difference warrants the co-existence of them as separate intersections, because the medium informs how players interact with the text, and different modes of interaction offer very different playing experiences. Yes-Anding is at the intersection of: [[Standup]] and [[Interactive Fiction]] [[<-|Convergences]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Antimimeticism When analyzing the nature of storyworlds, narratologists have three primary categories: mimetic storytelling, which mimics our actual world; nonmimetic storytelling, which follows its own logic and conventions separate from our world (e.g. fairy tales); and antimimetic storytelling, which actively resists convention or naturalization, working against the audience's urge to immerse themself in a story's world (Bell and Ensslin 6). The latter is an experimental space for “permanently defamiliarizing” narratives, ones so strange and illogical that the audience cannot make sense of them (Bell and Ensslin 8). Interpreting antimimetic narratives can be difficult, mostly because they are designed to resist such treatment. To this end, Bell and Ensslin propose the “reading strategy of ‘unnatural construction’” (34). This approach does not seek to make sense of the construction itself, but rather how it contributes to the text. Does alienating the audience in this way connect to its themes? When the presentation, not the content, is what draws attention, how does that transform the reading/playing experience? They argue questions like these are a more useful response to antimimetic techniques than attempting rationalization. Interactive works have a unique connection to medium-specific antimimeticism, the practice in which a text “defies the conventions of an existing, established medium” (Bell and Ensslin 20). In playable media, plenty of techniques and ideas that would be unthinkable elsewhere are commonplace, if not expected. For example, a character both dying and not dying at a certain place in the game world, or a branching narrative with no formalized chronology. As digital media continues to rapidly evolve, conventions within subgenres change too; things that might have once been antimimetic or strange may later become typical. Conventions are context-specific to place, time, and form, therefore works that defy or resist convention are equally varied. Antimimeticism intersects with: [[Theory of Comic Objects]] at [[Ambiguous Action]] [[Index]] [[Image]]Index [[Opening|Start]] [[Interactive Comedy]] [[Purpose]] [[Image]] [[Conclusion]] [[Convergences]] explored in this model: [[Puzzle Punchlines]] [[Interactive Gags]] [[Play Contract]] [[Betraying Trust]] [[Ambiguous Action]] [[Convention as Setup]] [[Limitation as Setup]] [[Casting Characters]] [[Sketched World]] [[Initiated Slapstick]] [[Yes-Anding]] [[Comedy]] and its subtopics: [[The Joke]] [[Play Theory]] [[Trust]] [[Theory of Comic Objects]] [[Literary Comedy]] [[Burlesque]] [[Sketch]] [[Slapstick]] [[Standup]] [[Playable Media]] and its subtopics: [[Puzzle]] [[Participatory]] [[Unnatural Narrative]] [[Antimimeticism]] [[Medium Specificity]] [[Metalepsis]] [[Hypertext]] [[Videogame]] [[Interactive Fiction]] [[Bibliography]]Purpose How do these two fields connect? How can designers account for the unpredictable actions of users when crafting comedy? What does it mean for the player to be the co-author of a joke? These questions guided my research as I conducted an interdisciplinary study to expand upon frames for analysis and creation of interactive comedy. In breaking down the wide disciplines of playable media and comedy into so many concepts, subgenres, and forms, my intent is not to pigeonhole these intersections to only fit their corresponding ideas. Discrete subcategories serve the theoretical space well, and they proved to be the best way to assemble this knowledge in a digestible and clear way. As will always be the case, there is a misalignment between the goals of a theorist and a creator. The intersections presented here highlight defining aspects of the concepts they connect. As stated in the introduction to //Video Games and Comedy//, all kinds of digital games “use computer technology—and its specific affordances and constraints—as co-creators and catalysts of comedy” (Giappone et al. 15). Interactive comedy covers an impressive range of media, and my goal is to contribute to a more sophisticated formalized understanding of what makes it tick, not to imply that certain techniques are only possible within certain niche fields. [[<-|Interactive Comedy]] [[Image]] [[Index]]Conclusion I made this framework as part of my research with the knowledge that I would not be able to fully flesh it out with the time and resources I had. My goal was to draw meaningful and varied connections between playable media and comedy, and I believe I was able to do that. I learned a lot about experimental narratology during this process, and it is an area I would like to continue researching. To further develop what I have found here, my first priority would be analyzing comedy as it exists in playable media, both games dedicated to it and ones where it presents itself incidentally, or even accidentally. Within the experimental space especially, most works are not primarily comedic, and I want to seek out how they approach interactive comedy. I believe further taxonomizing existing techniques would be useful, especially in multiplayer contexts, in addition to seeking out new ones that could theoretically be used. Comedy has just as much potential as any other genre to facilitate innovation in interactive storytelling, and a more sophisticated understanding of interactive comedy will help develop the construction and potential of all interactive digital media. The intersections of comedy and playable media are nothing short of the purpose of my research, and as a result this framework. In analyzing the ideas that come together to constitute these fields of study, certain similarities present themselves between the two. It is my belief that these connections are useful to player, critic, and designer, as they denote distinct ways comedic media can leverage uniquely digital forms of interaction. Understanding the nuanced ways audiences can engage with and co-author content, and deliberately incorporating this knowledge into future projects, is how we push the medium forward.
